constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: incidence
element.description: The incidence of the interaction, e.g. theoretical, observed
element.definition: The incidence of the interaction, e.g. theoretical, observed.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: management
element.definition: Actions for managing the interaction.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: item
element.description: The specific medication, food or laboratory test that interacts
element.definition: The specific medication, food or laboratory test that interacts.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: symptomConditionEffect
element.description: The situation in which the undesirable effect may manifest
element.definition: The situation in which the undesirable effect may manifest.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: classification
element.description: High level classification of the effect
element.definition: High level classification of the effect.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: frequencyOfOccurrence
element.description: How often the effect is seen
element.definition: How often the effect is seen.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: description
element.description: A textual definition of this warning, with formatting
element.definition: A textual definition of this warning, with formatting.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: code
element.description: A coded or unformatted textual definition of this warning
element.definition: A coded or unformatted textual definition of this warning.

binding.name: WarningType
binding.description: Classification of warning type.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: url
element.description: Canonical identifier for this code system, represented as a URI (globally unique) (Coding.system)
element.definition: An absolute URI that is used to identify this code system when it is referenced in a specification, model, design or an instance; also called its canonical identifier. This SHOULD be globally unique and SHOULD be a literal address at which at which an authoritative instance of this code system is (or will be) published. This URL can be the target of a canonical reference. It SHALL remain the same when the code system is stored on different servers. This is used in [Coding](datatypes.html#Coding).system.
element.comment:
Can be a urn:uuid: or a urn:oid: but real http: addresses are preferred. Multiple instances may share the same URL if they have a distinct version.
The determination of when to create a new version of a resource (same url, new version) vs. defining a new artifact is up to the author. Considerations for making this decision are found in [Technical and Business Versions](resource.html#versions).
In some cases, the resource can no longer be found at the stated url, but the url itself cannot change. Implementations can use the [meta.source](resource.html#meta) element to indicate where the current master source of the resource can be found.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: identifier
element.description: Additional identifier for the code system (business identifier)
element.definition: A formal identifier that is used to identify this code system when it is represented in other formats, or referenced in a specification, model, design or an instance.
element.comment: Typically, this is used for identifiers that can go in an HL7 V3 II (instance identifier) data type, and can then identify this code system outside of FHIR, where it is not possible to use the logical URI. Note that HL7 defines at least three identifiers for many of its code systems - the FHIR canonical URL, the OID and the V2 Table 0396 mnemonic code.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: version
element.description: Business version of the code system (Coding.version)
element.definition: The identifier that is used to identify this version of the code system when it is referenced in a specification, model, design or instance. This is an arbitrary value managed by the code system author and is not expected to be globally unique. For example, it might be a timestamp (e.g. yyyymmdd) if a managed version is not available. There is also no expectation that versions can be placed in a lexicographical sequence. This is used in [Coding](datatypes.html#Coding).version.
element.comment: There may be different code system instances that have the same identifier but different versions. The version can be appended to the url in a reference to allow a reference to a particular business version of the code system with the format [url]|[version].

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: name
element.description: Name for this code system (computer friendly)
element.definition: A natural language name identifying the code system. This name should be usable as an identifier for the module by machine processing applications such as code generation.
element.comment: The name is not expected to be globally unique. The name should be a simple alphanumeric type name to ensure that it is machine-processing friendly.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: title
element.description: Name for this code system (human friendly)
element.definition: A short, descriptive, user-friendly title for the code system.
element.comment: This name does not need to be machine-processing friendly and may contain punctuation, white-space, etc.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: status
element.definition: The date (and optionally time) when the code system resource was created or revised.
element.comment: Allows filtering of code systems that are appropriate for use versus not.

binding.name: PublicationStatus
binding.description: The lifecycle status of an artifact.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: experimental
element.description: For testing purposes, not real usage
element.definition: A Boolean value to indicate that this code system is authored for testing purposes (or education/evaluation/marketing) and is not intended to be used for genuine usage.
element.comment: Allows filtering of code systems that are appropriate for use versus not.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: date
element.definition: The date (and optionally time) when the code system was published. The date must change when the business version changes and it must change if the status code changes. In addition, it should change when the substantive content of the code system changes.
element.comment: Note that this is not the same as the resource last-modified-date, since the resource may be a secondary representation of the code system. Additional specific dates may be added as extensions or be found by consulting Provenances associated with past versions of the resource.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: publisher
element.description: Name of the publisher (organization or individual)
element.definition: The name of the organization or individual that published the code system.
element.comment: Usually an organization but may be an individual. The publisher (or steward) of the code system is the organization or individual primarily responsible for the maintenance and upkeep of the code system. This is not necessarily the same individual or organization that developed and initially authored the content. The publisher is the primary point of contact for questions or issues with the code system. This item SHOULD be populated unless the information is available from context.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: contact
element.definition: Contact details to assist a user in finding and communicating with the publisher.
element.comment: May be a web site, an email address, a telephone number, etc.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: description
element.description: Natural language description of the code system
element.definition: A free text natural language description of the code system from a consumer's perspective.
element.comment: This description can be used to capture details such as why the code system was built, comments about misuse, instructions for clinical use and interpretation, literature references, examples from the paper world, etc. It is not a rendering of the code system as conveyed in the 'text' field of the resource itself. This item SHOULD be populated unless the information is available from context (e.g. the language of the code system is presumed to be the predominant language in the place the code system was created).

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: useContext
element.description: The context that the content is intended to support
element.definition: The content was developed with a focus and intent of supporting the contexts that are listed. These contexts may be general categories (gender, age, ...) or may be references to specific programs (insurance plans, studies, ...) and may be used to assist with indexing and searching for appropriate code system instances.
element.comment: When multiple useContexts are specified, there is no expectation that all or any of the contexts apply.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: jurisdiction
element.description: Intended jurisdiction for code system (if applicable)
element.definition: A legal or geographic region in which the code system is intended to be used.
element.comment: It may be possible for the code system to be used in jurisdictions other than those for which it was originally designed or intended.

binding.name: Jurisdiction
binding.description: Countries and regions within which this artifact is targeted for use.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: purpose
element.description: Why this code system is defined
element.definition: Explanation of why this code system is needed and why it has been designed as it has.
element.comment: This element does not describe the usage of the code system. Instead, it provides traceability of ''why'' the resource is either needed or ''why'' it is defined as it is. This may be used to point to source materials or specifications that drove the structure of this code system.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: copyright
element.definition: A copyright statement relating to the code system and/or its contents. Copyright statements are generally legal restrictions on the use and publishing of the code system.
element.comment: ... Sometimes, the copyright differs between the code system and the codes that are included. The copyright statement should clearly differentiate between these when required.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: caseSensitive
element.description: If code comparison is case sensitive
element.definition: If code comparison is case sensitive when codes within this system are compared to each other.
element.comment: If this value is missing, then it is not specified whether a code system is case sensitive or not. When the rule is not known, Postel's law should be followed: produce codes with the correct case, and accept codes in any case. This element is primarily provided to support validation software.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: valueSet
element.description: Canonical reference to the value set with entire code system
element.definition: Canonical reference to the value set that contains the entire code system.
element.comment: The definition of the value set SHALL include all codes from this code system and only codes from this code system, and it SHALL be immutable.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: hierarchyMeaning
element.definition: The meaning of the hierarchy of concepts as represented in this resource.
element.comment: Note that other representations might have a different hierarchy or none at all, and represent the information using properties.

binding.name: CodeSystemHierarchyMeaning
binding.description: The meaning of the hierarchy of concepts in a code system.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: compositional
element.description: If code system defines a compositional grammar
element.definition: The code system defines a compositional (post-coordination) grammar.
element.comment: Note that the code system resource does not define what the compositional grammar is, only whether or not there is one.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: versionNeeded
element.definition: This flag is used to signify that the code system does not commit to concept permanence across versions. If true, a version must be specified when referencing this code system.
element.comment:
Best practice is that code systems do not redefine concepts, or that if concepts are redefined, a new code system definition is created. But this is not always possible, so some code systems may be defined as 'versionNeeded'.
Most code systems occasionally refine the displays defined for concepts between versions. Contexts in which the concept display values are validated may require that the version be specified for some code systems irrespective of the value of this property.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: content
element.definition: The extent of the content of the code system (the concepts and codes it defines) are represented in this resource instance.

binding.name: CodeSystemContentMode
binding.description: The extent of the content of the code system (the concepts and codes it defines) are represented in a code system resource.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: supplements
element.description: Canonical URL of Code System this adds designations and properties to
element.definition: The canonical URL of the code system that this code system supplement is adding designations and properties to.
element.comment: The most common use of a code system supplement is to add additional language support.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: count
element.description: Total concepts in the code system
element.definition: The total number of concepts defined by the code system. Where the code system has a compositional grammar, the basis of this count is defined by the system steward.
element.comment: The count of concepts defined in this resource cannot be more than this value but may be less for several reasons - see the content element.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: filter
element.description: Filter that can be used in a value set
element.definition: A filter that can be used in a value set compose statement when selecting concepts using a filter.
element.comment: Note that filters defined in code systems usually require custom code on the part of any terminology engine that will make them available for use in value set filters. For this reason, they are generally only seen in high value published terminologies.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: property
element.description: Additional information supplied about each concept
element.definition: A property defines an additional slot through which additional information can be provided about a concept.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: concept
element.definition: Concepts that are in the code system. The concept definitions are inherently hierarchical, but the definitions must be consulted to determine what the meanings of the hierarchical relationships are.
element.comment: If this is empty, it means that the code system resource does not represent the content of the code system.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: code
element.definition: A code - a text symbol - that uniquely identifies the concept within the code system.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: display
element.description: Text to display to the user
element.definition: A human readable string that is the recommended default way to present this concept to a user.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: definition
element.definition: The formal definition of the concept. The code system resource does not make formal definitions required, because of the prevalence of legacy systems. However, they are highly recommended, as without them there is no formal meaning associated with the concept.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: designation
element.definition: Additional representations for the concept - other languages, aliases, specialized purposes, used for particular purposes, etc.
element.comment: Concepts have both a ```display``` and an array of ```designation```. The display is equivalent to a special designation with an implied ```designation.use``` of "primary code" and a language equal to the [Resource Language](resource.html#language).

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: property
element.definition: A property value for this concept.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: concept
element.definition: Defines children of a concept to produce a hierarchy of concepts. The nature of the relationships is variable (is-a/contains/categorizes) - see hierarchyMeaning.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: language
element.definition: The language this designation is defined for.
element.comment: In the absence of a language, the resource language applies.

binding.name: Language
binding.description: IETF language tag

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: use
element.description: Details how this designation would be used
element.definition: A code that details how this designation would be used.
element.comment: If no use is provided, the designation can be assumed to be suitable for general display to a human user.

binding.name: ConceptDesignationUse
binding.description: Details of how a designation would be used.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: value
element.description: The text value for this designation
element.definition: The text value for this designation.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: code
element.definition: A code that is a reference to CodeSystem.property.code.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: value
element.description: Value of the property for this concept
element.definition: The value of this property.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: code
element.definition: The code that identifies this filter when it is used as a filter in [ValueSet](valueset.html#).compose.include.filter.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: description
element.description: How or why the filter is used
element.definition: A description of how or why the filter is used.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: operator
element.description: = | is-a | descendent-of | is-not-a | regex | in | not-in | generalizes | child-of | descendent-leaf | exists
element.definition: A list of operators that can be used with the filter.

binding.name: FilterOperator
binding.description: The kind of operation to perform as a part of a property based filter.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: value
element.description: What to use for the value
element.definition: A description of what the value for the filter should be.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: code
element.description: Identifies the property on the concepts, and when referred to in operations
element.definition: A code that is used to identify the property. The code is used internally (in CodeSystem.concept.property.code) and also externally, such as in property filters.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: uri
element.definition: Reference to the formal meaning of the property. One possible source of meaning is the [Concept Properties](codesystem-concept-properties.html) code system.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: description
element.description: Why the property is defined, and/or what it conveys
element.definition: A description of the property- why it is defined, and how its value might be used.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: type
element.description: code | Coding | string | integer | boolean | dateTime | decimal
element.definition: The type of the property value. Properties of type "code" contain a code defined by the code system (e.g. a reference to another defined concept).

binding.name: PropertyType
binding.description: The type of a property value.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: coding
element.description: Code defined by a terminology system
element.definition: A reference to a code defined by a terminology system.
element.comment: Codes may be defined very casually in enumerations, or code lists, up to very formal definitions such as SNOMED CT - see the HL7 v3 Core Principles for more information. Ordering of codings is undefined and SHALL NOT be used to infer meaning. Generally, at most only one of the coding values will be labeled as UserSelected = true.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: text
element.description: Plain text representation of the concept
element.definition: A human language representation of the concept as seen/selected/uttered by the user who entered the data and/or which represents the intended meaning of the user.
element.comment: Very often the text is the same as a displayName of one of the codings.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: concept
element.definition: A reference to a concept - e.g. the information is identified by it's general classto the degree of precision found in the terminology.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: reference
element.definition: A reference to a resource the provides exact details about the information being referenced.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: system
element.definition: The identification of the code system that defines the meaning of the symbol in the code.
element.comment: The URI may be an OID (urn:oid:...) or a UUID (urn:uuid:...). OIDs and UUIDs SHALL be references to the HL7 OID registry. Otherwise, the URI should come from HL7's list of FHIR defined special URIs or it should reference to some definition that establishes the system clearly and unambiguously.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: version
element.description: Version of the system - if relevant
element.definition: The version of the code system which was used when choosing this code. Note that a well-maintained code system does not need the version reported, because the meaning of codes is consistent across versions. However this cannot consistently be assured, and when the meaning is not guaranteed to be consistent, the version SHOULD be exchanged.
element.comment: Where the terminology does not clearly define what string should be used to identify code system versions, the recommendation is to use the date (expressed in FHIR date format) on which that version was officially published as the version date.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: code
element.description: Symbol in syntax defined by the system
element.definition: A symbol in syntax defined by the system. The symbol may be a predefined code or an expression in a syntax defined by the coding system (e.g. post-coordination).

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: display
element.definition: A representation of the meaning of the code in the system, following the rules of the system.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: userSelected
element.description: If this coding was chosen directly by the user
element.definition: Indicates that this coding was chosen by a user directly - e.g. off a pick list of available items (codes or displays).
element.comment: Amongst a set of alternatives, a directly chosen code is the most appropriate starting point for new translations. There is some ambiguity about what exactly 'directly chosen' implies, and trading partner agreement may be needed to clarify the use of this element and its consequences more completely.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: identifier
element.definition: Business identifiers assigned to this communication by the performer or other systems which remain constant as the resource is updated and propagates from server to server.
element.comment: This is a business identifier, not a resource identifier (see [discussion](resource.html#identifiers)). It is best practice for the identifier to only appear on a single resource instance, however business practices may occasionally dictate that multiple resource instances with the same identifier can exist - possibly even with different resource types. For example, multiple Patient and a Person resource instance might share the same social insurance number.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: instantiatesCanonical
element.definition: The URL pointing to a FHIR-defined protocol, guideline, orderset or other definition that is adhered to in whole or in part by this Communication.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: instantiatesUri
element.definition: The URL pointing to an externally maintained protocol, guideline, orderset or other definition that is adhered to in whole or in part by this Communication.
element.comment: This might be an HTML page, PDF, etc. or could just be a non-resolvable URI identifier.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: basedOn
element.definition: An order, proposal or plan fulfilled in whole or in part by this Communication.
element.comment: This must point to some sort of a 'Request' resource, such as CarePlan, CommunicationRequest, ServiceRequest, MedicationRequest, etc.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: partOf
element.description: Part of referenced event (e.g. Communication, Procedure)
element.definition: A larger event (e.g. Communication, Procedure) of which this particular communication is a component or step.
element.comment: The event the communication was part of - e.g. if you disclosed as "part" of counselling, it would be partOf that Procedure.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: inResponseTo
element.definition: Prior communication that this communication is in response to.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: status
element.description: preparation | in-progress | not-done | on-hold | stopped | completed | entered-in-error | unknown
element.definition: The status of the transmission.
element.comment: This element is labeled as a modifier because the status contains the codes aborted and entered-in-error that mark the communication as not currently valid.

binding.name: CommunicationStatus
binding.description: The status of the communication.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: statusReason
element.definition: Captures the reason for the current state of the Communication.
element.comment: This is generally only used for "exception" statuses such as "not-done", "suspended" or "aborted". The reason for performing the event at all is captured in reasonCode, not here.

binding.name: CommunicationNotDoneReason
binding.description: Codes for the reason why a communication did not happen.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: category
element.definition: The type of message conveyed such as alert, notification, reminder, instruction, etc.
element.comment: There may be multiple axes of categorization and one communication may serve multiple purposes.

binding.name: CommunicationCategory
binding.description: Codes for general categories of communications such as alerts, instructions, etc.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: priority
element.definition: Characterizes how quickly the planned or in progress communication must be addressed. Includes concepts such as stat, urgent, routine.
element.comment: Used to prioritize workflow (such as which communication to read first) when the communication is planned or in progress.

binding.name: CommunicationPriority
binding.description: Codes indicating the relative importance of a communication.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: medium
element.definition: A channel that was used for this communication (e.g. email, fax).

binding.name: CommunicationMedium
binding.description: Codes for communication mediums such as phone, fax, email, in person, etc.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: subject
element.definition: The patient or group that was the focus of this communication.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: topic
element.definition: Description of the purpose/content, similar to a subject line in an email.
element.comment: Communication.topic.text can be used without any codings.

binding.name: CommunicationTopic
binding.description: Codes describing the purpose or content of the communication.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: about
element.description: Resources that pertain to this communication
element.definition: Other resources that pertain to this communication and to which this communication should be associated.
element.comment: Don't use Communication.about element when a more specific element exists, such as basedOn or reasonReference.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: encounter
element.description: The Encounter during which this Communication was created
element.definition: The Encounter during which this Communication was created or to which the creation of this record is tightly associated.
element.comment: This will typically be the encounter the event occurred within, but some activities may be initiated prior to or after the official completion of an encounter but still be tied to the context of the encounter.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: sent
element.definition: The time when this communication was sent.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: received
element.definition: The time when this communication arrived at the destination.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: recipient
element.description: Who the information is shared with
element.definition: The entity (e.g. person, organization, clinical information system, care team or device) which is the target of the communication.
element.comment: If receipts need to be tracked by an individual, a separate resource instance will need to be created for each recipient. Multiple recipient communications are intended where either receipts are not tracked (e.g. a mass mail-out) or a receipt is captured in aggregate (all emails confirmed received by a particular time).

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: sender
element.definition: The entity (e.g. person, organization, clinical information system, or device) which is the source of the communication.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: reason
element.definition: The reason or justification for the communication.
element.comment: Textual reasons can be captured using reason.concept.text.

binding.name: CommunicationReason
binding.description: Codes for describing reasons for the occurrence of a communication.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: payload
element.definition: Text, attachment(s), or resource(s) that was communicated to the recipient.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: note
element.definition: Additional notes or commentary about the communication by the sender, receiver or other interested parties.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: content
element.definition: A communicated content (or for multi-part communications, one portion of the communication).
element.comment:
The content can be codified or textual. As an example of codified content, when working with machine generated communications, the payload may be drawn from a finite, terminology defined set of communications, especially for short, status update kinds of communications where more of a natural language approach isn't appropriate.
If the content isn't codified, contentCodeableConcept.text can be used.
When using contentCodeableConcept, the CodeableConcept is what is being communicated and is not a categorization of the content.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: identifier
element.definition: Business identifiers assigned to this communication request by the performer or other systems which remain constant as the resource is updated and propagates from server to server.
element.comment: This is a business identifier, not a resource identifier (see [discussion](resource.html#identifiers)). It is best practice for the identifier to only appear on a single resource instance, however business practices may occasionally dictate that multiple resource instances with the same identifier can exist - possibly even with different resource types. For example, multiple Patient and a Person resource instance might share the same social insurance number.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: basedOn
element.definition: A plan or proposal that is fulfilled in whole or in part by this request.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: replaces
element.definition: Completed or terminated request(s) whose function is taken by this new request.
element.comment: The replacement could be because the initial request was immediately rejected (due to an issue) or because the previous request was completed, but the need for the action described by the request remains ongoing.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: groupIdentifier
element.description: Composite request this is part of
element.definition: A shared identifier common to all requests that were authorized more or less simultaneously by a single author, representing the identifier of the requisition, prescription or similar form.
element.comment: Requests are linked either by a "basedOn" relationship (i.e. one request is fulfilling another) or by having a common requisition. Requests that are part of the same requisition are generally treated independently from the perspective of changing their state or maintaining them after initial creation.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: status
element.description: draft | active | on-hold | revoked | completed | entered-in-error | unknown
element.definition: The status of the proposal or order.

binding.name: CommunicationRequestStatus
binding.description: The status of the communication request.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: statusReason
element.definition: Captures the reason for the current state of the CommunicationRequest.
element.comment: This is generally only used for "exception" statuses such as "on-hold" or "revoked". The reason why the CommunicationRequest was created at all is captured in reasonCode, not here.

binding.name: CommunicationRequestStatusReason
binding.description: Codes identifying the reason for the current state of a request.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: intent
element.description: proposal | plan | directive | order | original-order | reflex-order | filler-order | instance-order | option
element.definition: Indicates the level of authority/intentionality associated with the CommunicationRequest and where the request fits into the workflow chain.
element.comment:
This element is expected to be immutable. E.g. A "proposal" instance should never change to be a "plan" instance or "order" instance. Instead, a new instance 'basedOn' the prior instance should be created with the new 'intent' value.
One exception to this is that the granularity of CommunicationRequest.intent is allowed to change. For example, a Request identified as an "order" might later be clarified to be a "filler-order". Or, in rarer cases (to meet recipient constraints), the reverse might also occur.

binding.name: CommunicationRequestIntent
binding.description: Codes indicating the degree of authority/intentionality associated with a request.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: category
element.definition: The type of message to be sent such as alert, notification, reminder, instruction, etc.
element.comment: There may be multiple axes of categorization and one communication request may serve multiple purposes.

binding.name: CommunicationCategory
binding.description: Codes for general categories of communications such as alerts, instruction, etc.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: priority
element.definition: Characterizes how quickly the proposed act must be initiated. Includes concepts such as stat, urgent, routine.

binding.name: CommunicationPriority
binding.description: Codes indicating the relative importance of a communication request.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: doNotPerform
element.description: True if request is prohibiting action
element.definition: If true indicates that the CommunicationRequest is asking for the specified action to *not* occur.
element.comment: The attributes provided with the request qualify what is not to be done.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: medium
element.definition: A channel that was used for this communication (e.g. email, fax).

binding.name: CommunicationMedium
binding.description: Codes for communication mediums such as phone, fax, email, in person, etc.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: subject
element.definition: The patient or group that is the focus of this communication request.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: about
element.description: Resources that pertain to this communication request
element.definition: Other resources that pertain to this communication request and to which this communication request should be associated.
element.comment: Don't use CommunicationRequest.about element when a more specific element exists, such as basedOn, reasonReference, or replaces.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: encounter
element.description: The Encounter during which this CommunicationRequest was created
element.definition: The Encounter during which this CommunicationRequest was created or to which the creation of this record is tightly associated.
element.comment: This will typically be the encounter the event occurred within, but some activities may be initiated prior to or after the official completion of an encounter but still be tied to the context of the encounter.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: payload
element.definition: Text, attachment(s), or resource(s) to be communicated to the recipient.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: occurrence
element.definition: The time when this communication is to occur.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: authoredOn
element.description: When request transitioned to being actionable
element.definition: For draft requests, indicates the date of initial creation. For requests with other statuses, indicates the date of activation.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: requester
element.description: Who asks for the information to be shared
element.definition: The device, individual, or organization who asks for the information to be shared.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: recipient
element.description: Who to share the information with
element.definition: The entity (e.g. person, organization, clinical information system, device, group, or care team) which is the intended target of the communication.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: informationProvider
element.definition: The entity (e.g. person, organization, clinical information system, or device) which is to be the source of the communication.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: reason
element.definition: Describes why the request is being made in coded or textual form.
element.comment: Textual reasons can be captured using reasonCode.text.

binding.name: CommunicationReason
binding.description: Codes for describing reasons for the occurrence of a communication.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: note
element.definition: Comments made about the request by the requester, sender, recipient, subject or other participants.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: content
element.definition: The communicated content (or for multi-part communications, one portion of the communication).
element.comment:
The content can be codified or textual. As an example of codified content, when working with machine generated communications, the payload may be drawn from a finite, terminology defined set of communications, especially for short, status update kinds of communications where more of a natural language approach isn't appropriate.
If the content isn't codified, contentCodeableConcept.text can be used.
When using contentCodeableConcept, the CodeableConcept is what is being communicated and is not a categorization of the content.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: url
element.description: Canonical identifier for this compartment definition, represented as a URI (globally unique)
element.definition: An absolute URI that is used to identify this compartment definition when it is referenced in a specification, model, design or an instance; also called its canonical identifier. This SHOULD be globally unique and SHOULD be a literal address at which at which an authoritative instance of this compartment definition is (or will be) published. This URL can be the target of a canonical reference. It SHALL remain the same when the compartment definition is stored on different servers.
element.comment:
Can be a urn:uuid: or a urn:oid: but real http: addresses are preferred. Multiple instances may share the same URL if they have a distinct version.
The determination of when to create a new version of a resource (same url, new version) vs. defining a new artifact is up to the author. Considerations for making this decision are found in [Technical and Business Versions](resource.html#versions).
In some cases, the resource can no longer be found at the stated url, but the url itself cannot change. Implementations can use the [meta.source](resource.html#meta) element to indicate where the current master source of the resource can be found.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: version
element.description: Business version of the compartment definition
element.definition: The identifier that is used to identify this version of the compartment definition when it is referenced in a specification, model, design or instance. This is an arbitrary value managed by the compartment definition author and is not expected to be globally unique. For example, it might be a timestamp (e.g. yyyymmdd) if a managed version is not available. There is also no expectation that versions can be placed in a lexicographical sequence.
element.comment: There may be different compartment definition instances that have the same identifier but different versions. The version can be appended to the url in a reference to allow a reference to a particular business version of the compartment definition with the format [url]|[version].

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: name
element.description: Name for this compartment definition (computer friendly)
element.definition: A natural language name identifying the compartment definition. This name should be usable as an identifier for the module by machine processing applications such as code generation.
element.comment: The name is not expected to be globally unique. The name should be a simple alphanumeric type name to ensure that it is machine-processing friendly.This is often the same as the code for the parameter, but does not need to be.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: status
element.definition: The status of this compartment definition. Enables tracking the life-cycle of the content.
element.comment: Allows filtering of compartment definitions that are appropriate for use versus not.

binding.name: PublicationStatus
binding.description: The lifecycle status of an artifact.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: experimental
element.description: For testing purposes, not real usage
element.definition: A Boolean value to indicate that this compartment definition is authored for testing purposes (or education/evaluation/marketing) and is not intended to be used for genuine usage.
element.comment: Allows filtering of compartment definitions that are appropriate for use versus not.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: date
element.definition: The date (and optionally time) when the compartment definition was published. The date must change when the business version changes and it must change if the status code changes. In addition, it should change when the substantive content of the compartment definition changes.
element.comment: Note that this is not the same as the resource last-modified-date, since the resource may be a secondary representation of the compartment definition. Additional specific dates may be added as extensions or be found by consulting Provenances associated with past versions of the resource.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: publisher
element.description: Name of the publisher (organization or individual)
element.definition: The name of the organization or individual that published the compartment definition.
element.comment: Usually an organization but may be an individual. The publisher (or steward) of the compartment definition is the organization or individual primarily responsible for the maintenance and upkeep of the compartment definition. This is not necessarily the same individual or organization that developed and initially authored the content. The publisher is the primary point of contact for questions or issues with the compartment definition. This item SHOULD be populated unless the information is available from context.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: contact
element.definition: Contact details to assist a user in finding and communicating with the publisher.
element.comment: May be a web site, an email address, a telephone number, etc.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: description
element.description: Natural language description of the compartment definition
element.definition: A free text natural language description of the compartment definition from a consumer's perspective.
element.comment: This description can be used to capture details such as why the compartment definition was built, comments about misuse, instructions for clinical use and interpretation, literature references, examples from the paper world, etc. It is not a rendering of the compartment definition as conveyed in the 'text' field of the resource itself. This item SHOULD be populated unless the information is available from context (e.g. the language of the compartment definition is presumed to be the predominant language in the place the compartment definition was created).

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: useContext
element.description: The context that the content is intended to support
element.definition: The content was developed with a focus and intent of supporting the contexts that are listed. These contexts may be general categories (gender, age, ...) or may be references to specific programs (insurance plans, studies, ...) and may be used to assist with indexing and searching for appropriate compartment definition instances.
element.comment: When multiple useContexts are specified, there is no expectation that all or any of the contexts apply.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: purpose
element.description: Why this compartment definition is defined
element.definition: Explanation of why this compartment definition is needed and why it has been designed as it has.
element.comment: This element does not describe the usage of the compartment definition. Instead, it provides traceability of ''why'' the resource is either needed or ''why'' it is defined as it is. This may be used to point to source materials or specifications that drove the structure of this compartment definition.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: code
element.definition: Which compartment this definition describes.
element.comment: Only the specification can define the compartments that can exist. Servers can choose to support them.

binding.name: CompartmentType
binding.description: Which type a compartment definition describes.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: search
element.description: Whether the search syntax is supported
element.definition: Whether the search syntax is supported,.
element.comment: Servers may define and use compartments to manage logical access without implementing the compartment related syntax.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: resource
element.description: How a resource is related to the compartment
element.definition: Information about how a resource is related to the compartment.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: code
element.definition: The name of a resource supported by the server.

binding.name: ResourceType
binding.description: One of the resource types defined as part of this version of FHIR.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: param
element.description: Search Parameter Name, or chained parameters
element.definition: The name of a search parameter that represents the link to the compartment. More than one may be listed because a resource may be linked to a compartment in more than one way,.
element.comment: If no search parameters are listed, then the resource is not linked to the compartment.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: documentation
element.description: Additional documentation about the resource and compartment
element.definition: Additional documentation about the resource and compartment.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: identifier
element.definition: A version-independent identifier for the Composition. This identifier stays constant as the composition is changed over time.
element.comment: Similar to ClinicalDocument/setId in CDA. See discussion in resource definition for how these relate.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: status
element.definition: The workflow/clinical status of this composition. The status is a marker for the clinical standing of the document.
element.comment:
If a composition is marked as withdrawn, the compositions/documents in the series, or data from the composition or document series, should never be displayed to a user without being clearly marked as untrustworthy. The flag "entered-in-error" is why this element is labeled as a modifier of other elements.
Some reporting work flows require that the original narrative of a final document never be altered; instead, only new narrative can be added. The composition resource has no explicit status for explicitly noting whether this business rule is in effect. This would be handled by an extension if required.

binding.name: CompositionStatus
binding.description: The workflow/clinical status of the composition.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: type
element.definition: Specifies the particular kind of composition (e.g. History and Physical, Discharge Summary, Progress Note). This usually equates to the purpose of making the composition.
element.comment: For Composition type, LOINC is ubiquitous and strongly endorsed by HL7. Most implementation guides will require a specific LOINC code, or use LOINC as an extensible binding.

binding.name: DocumentType
binding.description: Type of a composition.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: category
element.definition: A categorization for the type of the composition - helps for indexing and searching. This may be implied by or derived from the code specified in the Composition Type.
element.comment: This is a metadata field from [XDS/MHD](http://wiki.ihe.net/index.php?title=Mobile_access_to_Health_Documents_(MHD)).

binding.name: DocumentCategory
binding.description: High-level kind of a clinical document at a macro level.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: subject
element.description: Who and/or what the composition is about
element.definition: Who or what the composition is about. The composition can be about a person, (patient or healthcare practitioner), a device (e.g. a machine) or even a group of subjects (such as a document about a herd of livestock, or a set of patients that share a common exposure).
element.comment: For clinical documents, this is usually the patient.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: encounter
element.definition: Describes the clinical encounter or type of care this documentation is associated with.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: date
element.definition: The composition editing time, when the composition was last logically changed by the author.
element.comment: The Last Modified Date on the composition may be after the date of the document was attested without being changed.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: author
element.description: Who and/or what authored the composition
element.definition: Identifies who is responsible for the information in the composition, not necessarily who typed it in.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: title
element.definition: Official human-readable label for the composition.
element.comment: For many compositions, the title is the same as the text or a display name of Composition.type (e.g. a "consultation" or "progress note"). Note that CDA does not make title mandatory, but there are no known cases where it is useful for title to be omitted, so it is mandatory here. Feedback on this requirement is welcome during the trial use period.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: confidentiality
element.definition: The code specifying the level of confidentiality of the Composition.
element.comment: The exact use of this element, and enforcement and issues related to highly sensitive documents are out of scope for the base specification, and delegated to implementation profiles (see security section). This element is labeled as a modifier because highly confidential documents must not be treated as if they are not.

binding.name: DocumentConfidentiality
binding.description: Codes specifying the level of confidentiality of the composition.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: attester
element.definition: A participant who has attested to the accuracy of the composition/document.
element.comment: Only list each attester once.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: custodian
element.definition: Identifies the organization or group who is responsible for ongoing maintenance of and access to the composition/document information.
element.comment: This is useful when documents are derived from a composition - provides guidance for how to get the latest version of the document. This is optional because this is sometimes not known by the authoring system, and can be inferred by context. However, it is important that this information be known when working with a derived document, so providing a custodian is encouraged.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: relatesTo
element.definition: Relationships that this composition has with other compositions or documents that already exist.
element.comment: A document is a version specific composition.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: event
element.definition: The clinical service, such as a colonoscopy or an appendectomy, being documented.
element.comment: The event needs to be consistent with the type element, though can provide further information if desired.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: section
element.definition: The root of the sections that make up the composition.

constraint.name: cmp-1
constraint.message: A section must contain at least one of text, entries, or sub-sections

constraint.name: cmp-2
constraint.message: A section can only have an emptyReason if it is empty

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: mode
element.definition: The type of attestation the authenticator offers.

binding.name: CompositionAttestationMode
binding.description: The way in which a person authenticated a composition.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: time
element.definition: When the composition was attested by the party.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: party
element.definition: Who attested the composition in the specified way.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: code
element.description: Code(s) that apply to the event being documented
element.definition: This list of codes represents the main clinical acts, such as a colonoscopy or an appendectomy, being documented. In some cases, the event is inherent in the typeCode, such as a "History and Physical Report" in which the procedure being documented is necessarily a "History and Physical" act.
element.comment: An event can further specialize the act inherent in the typeCode, such as where it is simply "Procedure Report" and the procedure was a "colonoscopy". If one or more eventCodes are included, they SHALL NOT conflict with the values inherent in the classCode, practiceSettingCode or typeCode, as such a conflict would create an ambiguous situation. This short list of codes is provided to be used as key words for certain types of queries.

binding.name: DocumentEventType
binding.description: This list of codes represents the main clinical acts being documented.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: period
element.description: The period covered by the documentation
element.definition: The period of time covered by the documentation. There is no assertion that the documentation is a complete representation for this period, only that it documents events during this time.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: detail
element.definition: The description and/or reference of the event(s) being documented. For example, this could be used to document such a colonoscopy or an appendectomy.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: title
element.definition: The label for this particular section. This will be part of the rendered content for the document, and is often used to build a table of contents.
element.comment: The title identifies the section for a human reader. The title must be consistent with the narrative of the resource that is the target of the section.content reference. Generally, sections SHOULD have titles, but in some documents, it is unnecessary or inappropriate. Typically, this is where a section has subsections that have their own adequately distinguishing title, or documents that only have a single section. Most Implementation Guides will make section title to be a required element.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: code
element.definition: A code identifying the kind of content contained within the section. This must be consistent with the section title.
element.comment:
The code identifies the section for an automated processor of the document. This is particularly relevant when using profiles to control the structure of the document.
If the section has content (instead of sub-sections), the section.code does not change the meaning or interpretation of the resource that is the content of the section in the comments for the section.code.

binding.name: CompositionSectionType
binding.description: Classification of a section of a composition/document.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: author
element.description: Who and/or what authored the section
element.definition: Identifies who is responsible for the information in this section, not necessarily who typed it in.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: focus
element.description: Who/what the section is about, when it is not about the subject of composition
element.definition: The actual focus of the section when it is not the subject of the composition, but instead represents something or someone associated with the subject such as (for a patient subject) a spouse, parent, fetus, or donor. If not focus is specified, the focus is assumed to be focus of the parent section, or, for a section in the Composition itself, the subject of the composition. Sections with a focus SHALL only include resources where the logical subject (patient, subject, focus, etc.) matches the section focus, or the resources have no logical subject (few resources).
element.comment: Typically, sections in a doument are about the subject of the document, whether that is a patient, or group of patients, location, or device, or whatever. For some kind of documents, some sections actually contain data about related entities. Typical examples are a section in a newborn discharge summary concerning the mother, or family history documents, with a section about each family member, though there are many other examples.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: text
element.description: Text summary of the section, for human interpretation
element.definition: A human-readable narrative that contains the attested content of the section, used to represent the content of the resource to a human. The narrative need not encode all the structured data, but is required to contain sufficient detail to make it "clinically safe" for a human to just read the narrative.
element.comment: Document profiles may define what content should be represented in the narrative to ensure clinical safety.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: mode
element.definition: How the entry list was prepared - whether it is a working list that is suitable for being maintained on an ongoing basis, or if it represents a snapshot of a list of items from another source, or whether it is a prepared list where items may be marked as added, modified or deleted.
element.comment: This element is labeled as a modifier because a change list must not be misunderstood as a complete list.

binding.name: SectionMode
binding.description: The processing mode that applies to this section.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: orderedBy
element.definition: Specifies the order applied to the items in the section entries.
element.comment: Applications SHOULD render ordered lists in the order provided, but MAY allow users to re-order based on their own preferences as well. If there is no order specified, the order is unknown, though there may still be some order.

binding.name: SectionEntryOrder
binding.description: What order applies to the items in the entry.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: entry
element.description: A reference to data that supports this section
element.definition: A reference to the actual resource from which the narrative in the section is derived.
element.comment: If there are no entries in the list, an emptyReason SHOULD be provided.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: emptyReason
element.definition: If the section is empty, why the list is empty. An empty section typically has some text explaining the empty reason.
element.comment: The various reasons for an empty section make a significant interpretation to its interpretation. Note that this code is for use when the entire section content has been suppressed, and not for when individual items are omitted - implementers may consider using a text note or a flag on an entry in these cases.

binding.name: SectionEmptyReason
binding.description: If a section is empty, why it is empty.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: section
element.definition: A nested sub-section within this section.
element.comment: Nested sections are primarily used to help human readers navigate to particular portions of the document.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: url

element.definition: An absolute URI that is used to identify this concept map when it is referenced in a specification, model, design or an instance; also called its canonical identifier. This SHOULD be globally unique and SHOULD be a literal address at which at which an authoritative instance of this concept map is (or will be) published. constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

constraint.name: ele-1

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.description: Name for this concept map (computer friendly)
element.definition: A natural language name identifying the concept map. This name should be usable as an identifier for the module by machine processing applications such as code generation.
element.comment: The name is not expected to be globally unique. The name should be a simple alphanumeric type name to ensure that it is machine-processing friendly.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: title
element.description: Name for this concept map (human friendly)
element.definition: A short, descriptive, user-friendly title for the concept map.
element.comment: This name does not need to be machine-processing friendly and may contain punctuation, white-space, etc.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: status
element.definition: The status of this concept map. Enables tracking the life-cycle of the content.
element.comment: Allows filtering of concept maps that are appropriate for use versus not.

binding.name: PublicationStatus
binding.description: The lifecycle status of an artifact.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: experimental
element.description: For testing purposes, not real usage
element.definition: A Boolean value to indicate that this concept map is authored for testing purposes (or education/evaluation/marketing) and is not intended to be used for genuine usage.
element.comment: Allows filtering of concept maps that are appropriate for use versus not.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: date
element.definition: The date (and optionally time) when the concept map was published. The date must change when the business version changes and it must change if the status code changes. In addition, it should change when the substantive content of the concept map changes.
element.comment: Note that this is not the same as the resource last-modified-date, since the resource may be a secondary representation of the concept map. Additional specific dates may be added as extensions or be found by consulting Provenances associated with past versions of the resource.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: publisher
element.description: Name of the publisher (organization or individual)
element.definition: The name of the organization or individual that published the concept map.
element.comment: Usually an organization but may be an individual. The publisher (or steward) of the concept map is the organization or individual primarily responsible for the maintenance and upkeep of the concept map. This is not necessarily the same individual or organization that developed and initially authored the content. The publisher is the primary point of contact for questions or issues with the concept map. This item SHOULD be populated unless the information is available from context.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: contact
element.definition: Contact details to assist a user in finding and communicating with the publisher.
element.comment: May be a web site, an email address, a telephone number, etc.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: description
element.description: Natural language description of the concept map
element.definition: A free text natural language description of the concept map from a consumer's perspective.
element.comment: The description is not intended to describe the semantics of the concept map. The description should capture its intended use, which is needed for ensuring integrity for its use in models across future changes.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: useContext
element.description: The context that the content is intended to support
element.definition: The content was developed with a focus and intent of supporting the contexts that are listed. element.comment: When multiple useContexts are specified, there is no expectation that all or any of the contexts apply.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: jurisdiction
element.description: Intended jurisdiction for concept map (if applicable)
element.definition: A legal or geographic region in which the concept map is intended to be used.
element.comment: It may be possible for the concept map to be used in jurisdictions other than those for which it was originally designed or intended.

binding.name: Jurisdiction
binding.description: Countries and regions within which this artifact is targeted for use.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.name: purpose
element.description: Why this concept map is defined
element.definition: Explanation of why this concept map is needed and why it has been designed as it has.
element.comment: This element does not describe the usage of the concept map. Instead, it provides traceability of ''why'' the resource is either needed or ''why'' it is defined as it is. This may be used to point to source materials or specifications that drove the structure of this concept map.

constraint.name: ele-1
constraint.message: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children
